  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where should I go to university?",
  "response": "Choosing a university is a highly personal decision that depends on various factors such as your academic interests, career goals, financial situation, and personal preferences. Here are some steps you can take to help you make the best decision:\n\n1. **Identify Your Interests and Goals:**\n   - What subjects are you passionate about?\n   - What career do you envision for yourself?\n   - Do you prefer a large university or a smaller college?\n\n2. **Research Universities:**\n   - Look for universities that offer strong programs in your area of interest.\n   - Consider the location, campus facilities, student life, and extracurricular opportunities.\n   - Check university rankings and reviews for an overall idea of their reputation.\n\n3. **Consider Financial Aspects:**\n   - Evaluate tuition fees, available scholarships, financial aid, and living expenses.\n   - Consider the return on investment, such as job placement rates and alumni success.\n\n4. **Visit Campuses:**\n   - If possible, visit the campuses of the universities you are considering.\n   - Talk to current students, faculty, and admissions staff to get a feel for the environment.\n\n5. **Evaluate Support Services:**\n   - Look into academic advising, career services, mental health support, and other resources available to students.\n\n6. **Reflect on Personal Fit:**\n   - Consider the culture and values of the university and whether they align with your own.\n   - Think about the diversity and inclusivity of the student body.\n\nFinally, make a list of your top choices and weigh the pros and cons of each. Trust your instincts and choose the university where you believe you will thrive academically, socially, and personally.",
